[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(32) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Where he worshipped God.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "where men worship. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The original indicates a customary act. David had taken the road over the crest of the Mount of Olives, and there, in all probability, was one of those “high places” which abounded in Israel.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Hushai the Archite.—His place is mentioned in Joshua 16:2 as on the border between Ephraim and Benjamin, and he may have been at his own home when the rebellion broke out. His coming appears as the beginning of the answer to David’s prayer in 2Samuel 15:31.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Hushai the Archite.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—His place is mentioned in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Joshua 16:2",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " as on the border between Ephraim and Benjamin, and he may have been at his own home when the rebellion broke out. His coming appears as the beginning of the answer to David’s prayer in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 15:31",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Samuel 15:32",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 15:32",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "The top of the mount, where he worshipped — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Looking, doubtless, toward Jerusalem, where the ark and tabernacle, which he had made for it, were. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Hushai, the Archite came to meet him ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Probably he was from Archi, a city in the tribe of Ephraim, (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 16:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",) and coming to Jerusalem, was made one of David’s privy council because of his wisdom; otherwise, it is not likely that Absalom would so readily have entertained him, and admitted him to his secrets. The coming of Hushai just at this time seems to have been ordered by God’s peculiar providence, in answer to David’s prayer mentioned in the preceding verse. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "With his coat rent, and earth upon his head — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In token of his great sorrow on David’s account.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "15:31-37 David prays not against Ahithophel's person, but against his counsel. He prayed this, in firm belief that God has all hearts in his hand, and tongues also. But we must second our prayers with endeavours, and David did so, else we tempt God. But we do not find wisdom and simplicity so united in any mere man, that we can perceive nothing which needs forgiveness. Yet, when the Son of David was treated with all possible treachery and cruelty, his wisdom, meekness, candour, and patience, were perfect. Him let us follow, cleave to, and serve, in life and in death.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Render ... \"when David was come to the top of the mount where people worship God.\" The top here, and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 16:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is used almost as a proper name. No doubt there was a high-place upon the top of the Mount of Olives. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "32. when David was come to the top of the mount, where he worshipped—looking towards Jerusalem, where were the ark and tabernacle.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Hushai the Archite—A native of Archi, on the frontiers of Benjamin and Ephraim (Jos 16:2). Comparing the prayer against Ahithophel with the counsel to Hushai, we see how strongly a spirit of fervent piety was combined in his character with the devices of an active and far-seeing policy.   ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
